-- Graded Choice: Axiom of Choice at Weight < 1
--
-- NOTE: This file DEMONSTRATES the proof checker syntax.
-- The actual metatheory is formalized in agda/ProbTT/GradedChoice.agda
--
-- LITERATURE: This is more novel than Gödel/consistency work.
-- Related: constructive choice principles (Martin-Löf), realizability.
-- The "weight of AC" idea is ProbTT-specific.
--
-- Classical AC: For any family of non-empty sets, there exists a choice function
-- Problem: Non-constructive, leads to paradoxes (Banach-Tarski)
--
-- ProbTT alternative: Partial choice at high weight
-- - Finite choice: weight 1 (always works)
-- - Countable choice: weight approaches 1 but may not reach it
-- - Uncountable choice: weight strictly < 1
--
-- Key insight: Paradoxes require weight 1 to be fully realized

-- Finite choice is always possible at weight 1
-- For any finite family {A_1, ..., A_n} of non-empty sets,
-- we can construct a choice function explicitly
postulate finite_choice : Finite_Choice 〔 1 〕

-- Finite induction: if we can choose from n sets, we can choose from n+1
derive choice_step : Choice_n_plus_1 〔 1 〕 from finite_choice by induction

-- For countable families, each finite prefix has a choice function
-- The limit is the full choice function, but the limit may not be achieved
-- Weight = lim_{n→∞} (product of individual weights)
-- If each choice has weight 1-ε_n, total weight = ∏(1-ε_n)
-- This can be < 1 even if each factor is close to 1

-- Countable choice at weight approaching 1
provable countable_choice_approx : Countable_Choice 〔 w 〕

-- The weight w satisfies: for any ε > 0, w > 1 - ε for finite prefixes
-- But w may be < 1 in the limit

-- Uncountable choice (full AC) would require weight 1
-- But this may not be achievable

-- Banach-Tarski decomposition:
-- The paradoxical decomposition exists at some weight w < 1
-- This means: the mathematical object is "partially constructed"
-- At weight < 1, it cannot be physically realized

postulate bt_decomposition : Banach_Tarski 〔 w 〕

-- The key constraint: w < 1
-- This is NOT a postulate - it follows from the construction
-- Banach-Tarski requires infinitely many non-constructive choices
-- Each choice contributes a factor slightly < 1
-- The product is strictly < 1

-- Comparison with constructive mathematics:
-- Constructive: AC fails entirely (no choice function)
-- Classical: AC holds fully (weight 1)
-- ProbTT: AC holds at weight < 1 (partial choice)
--
-- ProbTT is more informative:
-- - We know something exists (weight > 0)
-- - We know it's not fully constructible (weight < 1)
-- - The weight quantifies how "close to constructible" it is

-- Physical interpretation:
-- Weight < 1 means "theoretically possible but not physically realizable"
-- Banach-Tarski at w < 1 correctly predicts: you can't actually do it
-- This resolves the apparent paradox
